    <statement><p>Add or subtract the rational expressions to a single rational expression and then simplify. If applicable, state the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{x^{2}-12}{x^{2}-4x}-\frac{x+3}{x}} =}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{1}{x-4}, x\ne 0</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{x^{2}-12}{x^{2}-4x}-\frac{x+3}{x}} 
      \amp = {\frac{x^{2}-12}{x\mathopen{}\left(x-4\right)}-\frac{x+3}{x}}  \\
      \amp = {\frac{x^{2}-12}{x\mathopen{}\left(x-4\right)}-\frac{x+3}{x}} \cdot \frac{(x - 4)}{(x - 4)} \\
      \amp = {\frac{x^{2}-12}{x\mathopen{}\left(x-4\right)}-\frac{\left(x+3\right)\mathopen{}\left(x-4\right)}{x\mathopen{}\left(x-4\right)}} \\
      \amp = {\frac{x^{2}-12-\left(x+3\right)\mathopen{}\left(x-4\right)}{x\mathopen{}\left(x-4\right)}} \\
      \amp = {\frac{x^{2}-12-\left(x^{2}-x-12\right)}{x\mathopen{}\left(x-4\right)}} \\
      \amp = {\frac{x^{2}-12-x^{2}+x+12}{x\mathopen{}\left(x-4\right)}} \\
      \amp = {\frac{x}{x\mathopen{}\left(x-4\right)}} \\
      \amp = {\frac{1}{x-4}, x\ne 0}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factor <m>{x}</m> was canceled, the domain condition lost during the simplification is <m>x \ne {0}</m>.</p>
</solution>
